<div style="background:#fff;"><div style="max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:8px 48px 56px;"><div style="margin-bottom:8px;"><div style="margin-bottom:26px;"><h2 style="font-family:var(--font-display);font-size:28px;font-weight:600;color:var(--ink);line-height:1.2;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin:0;">Frequently asked questions</h2></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:var(--radius-card);overflow:hidden;background:#fff;">
      <details class="sc-faq" open>
      <summary>When does COB make more sense than a packaged part?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">When assembly height, unit cost at volume, or board area are the binding constraints. COB removes the IC package, so the stack-up is thinner and there’s no package cost — it’s common in displays, sensors, RFID, and consumer modules.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>What wire and pitch can you bond?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">Gold ball bond from 18 µm wire and aluminium wedge bond for power devices, with bond pitch down to 60 µm. Bonds are pull- and shear-tested to MIL-STD-883 methods.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>Can COB and SMT run on the same board?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">Yes. A board can carry surface-mount components and chip-on-board die together — the COB step is integrated into the line rather than run as a separate program.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>What quality systems cover COB?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">ISO 9001 group-wide, IATF 16949 on automotive work, ISO 13485 on medical. Bonding runs in cleanroom-controlled, ESD-managed areas meeting ANSI/ESD S20.20.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>Do you protect customer designs and IP?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">An NDA is signed before any die, BOM, or CAD file is shared. Build areas are access-controlled and a program can be fenced to a dedicated line on request.</div>
    </details>
    </div>
  </div></div></div>

